<DOC><DOCNO> AP900822-0127 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-90 2000EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Dadaglio     08-22 0222</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Dadaglio,0228</SECOND><HEAD>Italian Cardinal Luigi Dadaglio Dies at Age 75</HEAD><DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Italian Cardinal Luigi Dadaglio, who heldseveral Vatican diplomatic posts in North and South America, diedWednesday at the age of 75.   The Vatican said Dadaglio had been hospitalized at Rome'sPoliclinico Gemelli hospital for several days with a heart ailment.   Born in northern Italy's Piedmont region, Dadaglio was ordaineda priest in 1937 and joined the Vatican Secretariat of State fiveyears later.   He went on to serve in Vatican diplomatic missions in Haiti,Dominican Republic, the United States, Canada, Australia, Colombia,Venezuela and Spain. In the United States, he served in Washingtonfrom 1950-53.   While Dadaglio was posted in Madrid, the Vatican and the Spanishgovernment signed five accords in 1979 regulating church-staterelations.   Elevated to cardinal by Pope John Paul II in 1985, he helpedorganize activities marking the church's Marian Year in 1987-88.   In a message of condolence, the pope praised Dadaglio for his``long and generous service in multiple posts carried out withcompetence and dedication on behalf of the church and the HolySee.''   Dadaglio's death brings the number of members of the College ofCardinals to 145. Of those, 109 are under the age of 80 and thuseligible to take part in a conclave to elect a new pope.</TEXT></DOC>